Question: How do you believe ACME should better support organizations and cultural leaders?

Response ID: resp_338
Response Text: • Find ways to have lived experience expressed narratively in the application (which can influence score among enlightened panelists/evaluators), but not as an exclusionary eligibility threshold as it was in the pilot.

• Write new guidelines to obtain enlightened panelists WHO HAVE ARTS EXPERTISE in the particular specialty being evaluated.

• Audience served must be the PRIMARY scoring factor. This is public money, so it should be used for the public good. Gathering specifics about this will also help ACME with hard data to proclaim economic impact of the arts.

• FINAL REPORTS must be detailed, provide links to legitimate backup, and must ALL be incorporated into impact summaries. With only 10% of final reports now reviewed, we are losing the data to help us proclaim economic impact. This is an example of a shocking logic gap and lack of initiative in the programs as run by EDD. IF IT TAKES AN ADDITIONAL EMPLOYEE TO DO COMPLETE FINAL REPORT SUMMARY WORK, THAT'S A GREAT USE OF A POSITION. That position should NOT be a third-party administrator. It is the very soul of the work: HOW DID THE FUNDING IMPACT AUSTIN AUDIENCES? — with data to back it up! 

• Artistic merit must be restored as the SECONDARY scoring consideration to honor the public investment.

• The TERTIARY scoring consideration should be ARTISTS PAID. How much? How many? The more artists paid well, the higher the grant allowance should be. 

• Incorporate a professionalizing pipeline structure for all arts grants - something like emerging, developing, institutional, featured...?) to point all applicants toward growth and professionalization. 

• LARGE grants should be reserved for groups with the capacity already in place to manage them according to best practices — to protect public investment/good stewardship of public funds. Incorporate inverse proportionality for institutional-level funding — i.e., the % of allowable budget funded by City dollars goes down as growth happens. This requires larger orgs to grow healthfully -- diversifying fundraising, finding corporate investment partners, and conducting business plan optimizations — to keep the city from giving more and more as they grow and grow forever. Yet, it enables institutional orgs to continue to receive funding at some level no matter how big they get. 

• Conversely, emerging artists/groups should be funded in amounts commensurate w/ their development and capacity to manage the investment well (let's articulate how to measure that capacity)

• Institutions that support the whole ecosystem should receive appropriate support

• Arts Services institutions can be strategic extensions of ACME effectiveness if partnerships are clear and developed with intention according to expertise. They can set applicants up for more successful use of granted funds. For example:
- TALA can teach GAAP — or help with implementation — for applicants to reach improved capacity
- Fiscal Sponsors must meet minimum standards established by the National Network of Fiscal Sponsors
- Create official collaborations between ACME Marketing and subsector arts services groups to streamline info consolidation for automated public consumption. Visit Austin can be a component, but not the owner of this. Visit Austin is not collaborative. Nor does it serve Austinites well.

• We should build a mechanism to ATTRACT businesses into making arts philanthropy a priority. THIS MAY NEED TO BE A NEW CITY hobnobbing/nonprofit imposition. Hydrate Austin's philanthropic desert.

• Creative spaces need City support and coordination. SpaceFinder-type searchable public database for clear pricing and easy booking accessible to all. Database should be managed by a City employee to increase creative space optimization and connect ACME to Rally Austin to nonprofits!

• Restore CSAP. Creative Spaces can't grow to meet potential optimization without funding.

• Thrive needs fixing yesterday to help arts group not experience funding gaps.

